Quis circum pagos] Suetonius says of Augustus (c. 45) that he was very fond of observing boxers, “ et maxime Latinos ε nou legitimos atque ordinarios modo sed et catervarios oppidanos inter angustias vicorum pugnantes temere ac sine arte.” These latter are what Horace alludes to: boxers who went about the streets and the country villages and fought for the amuse- ment of the inhabitants and for what they could pick up. Horace does not merely mean what took place at the Paganalia and· Compitalia, but frequently. ‘ Coronari Olympia' is a Greek way of speaking.
